In this work, the multiple impacts of precipitation were found obvious in the phase-decomposed TiNbTa 0.5 ZrAl 0.5 alloys, as shown in Fig.  9 (a). The precipitation of HCP phase (HEA1200) leads to higher strength, while the precipitation of BCC phase (HEA800) leads to lower one, compared with the single BCC solid solution phase (HEA1500).

The hard HCP precipitates make the HEA1200 stronger but more brittle (240 MPa increasing in yield strength and 4% decreasing in plasticity), while the soft BCC precipitates make the HEA800 softer but more ductile (190 MPa decreasing in yield strength and 12 % increasing in plasticity).
